[Event "The Game of the Century"]
[Site "New York"]
[Date "1956.10.17"]
[White "Donald Byrne"]
[Black "Robert James Fischer"]
[Result "0-1"]

{13-year-old Bobby Fischer plays what has been called "The Game of the Century" against one of America's strongest players. A queen sacrifice for the ages.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. d4 O-O 5. Bf4 d5 {Fischer strikes in the center immediately. The Gruenfeld-like structure gives Black counterplay against d4.} 6. Qb3 dxc4 7. Qxc4 c6 8. e4 Nbd7 9. Rd1 Nb6 10. Qc5 Bg4 11. Bg5 {Pinning the knight.} (11. Be2 {Was safer, maintaining a solid position.}) Na4!! {A stunning piece sacrifice. Fischer offers the knight to destroy White's queenside and open lines.} 12. Qa3 (12. Nxa4 Nxe4 {Threatening ...Qa5+ and ...Nxc5.} 13. Qc1 Qa5+ 14. b4 Qxa4 {Black recovers the piece with advantage.}) Nxc3 13. bxc3 Nxe4! {A second pawn falls, opening the position for Black's pieces.} 14. Bxe7 Qb6 {Now Fischer begins his counterattack. The threat is ...Nxc3, forking the king and rook.} 15. Bc4 Nxc3! 16. Bc5 Rfe8+ 17. Kf1 Be6!! {The key move of the game. Fischer offers his queen!} (17... Qb5+ {Was also strong.} 18. Kg1 Nxd1 {Winning exchange.}) 18. Bxb6 Bxc4+ 19. Kg1 Ne2+ 20. Kf1 Nxd4+ {The discovered check wins back material.} 21. Kg1 Ne2+ 22. Kf1 Nc3+ 23. Kg1 axb6 {Fischer has finally captured the bishop. Black has rook, bishop, and knight for the queen — plus a dominating position.} 24. Qb4 Ra4! 25. Qxb6 Nxd1 {Black wins the exchange and is completely winning.} 26. h3 Rxa2 27. Kh2 Nxf2 28. Re1 Rxe1 29. Qd8+ Bf8 30. Nxe1 Bd5 {Black's pieces dominate the board. There is no defence.} 31. Nf3 Ne4 32. Qb8 b5 {The passed pawn will decide the game.} 33. h4 h5 34. Ne5 Kg7 35. Kg1 Bc5+ 36. Kf1 Ng3+ 37. Ke1 Bb4+ 38. Kd1 Bb3+ 39. Kc1 Ne2+ 40. Kb1 Nc3+ 41. Kc1 Ra1# {Checkmate! A 13-year-old's masterpiece that shook the chess world.} 0-1
